WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
All right, hey everybody, I'm Michael Chow and this is Rich Iannone, and we wanted to

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:12.540
talk today about how making beautiful, publication quality tables in Python is possible in 2024.

00:00:12.540 --> 00:00:15.660
And we're really hoping that at the end, you don't just think that they're possible, but

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:17.320
a total delight.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:23.639
So just to give you a little bit of background, we are software engineers at PositPVC, and

00:00:23.639 --> 00:00:30.639
between the two of us, we have two PhDs, two dogs, and five cats, and we are fanatics

00:00:30.639 --> 00:00:32.279
of table display.

00:00:32.279 --> 00:00:37.360
We're just so interested in beautiful, publication-ready tables.

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:39.520
We each have two and a half cats.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:40.520
That's the joke.

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:41.520
Right.

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:42.520
That's the key.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:49.680
Yeah, what I mean by display tables and publication-ready tables is less of the table on the left, which

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:51.900
is a polar's data frame.

00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:54.439
So this is like a raw data frame.

00:00:54.439 --> 00:00:58.740
If you're a data frame plumber, you're a data scientist and you're working on the data,

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:00.740
this view makes sense.

00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:03.619
You know, the column names have underscores in them.

00:01:03.619 --> 00:01:09.739
You can see the types of the columns, and you can really see the nitty-gritty raw values.

00:01:09.739 --> 00:01:15.180
We mean less of that kind of table that has its guts hanging out for analysis, and more

00:01:15.180 --> 00:01:19.860
of the table on the right, which is a table that you might send to someone if you're trying

00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:23.220
to convey something about the data.

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:25.099
So this is the table we'll be talking about.

00:01:25.099 --> 00:01:29.779
It's a coffee table, and we'll be walking through it today.

00:01:29.779 --> 00:01:33.459
Just to give you a sense of where we'll be going, first we want to talk about tables

00:01:33.459 --> 00:01:39.739
as data visualization, then key ingredients to creating a beautiful display table, and

00:01:39.739 --> 00:01:44.699
then last, some more advanced considerations when creating tables for display.

00:01:44.699 --> 00:01:47.500
So I'll be talking about our table goals.

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:50.379
So basically the first part of the talk.

00:01:50.379 --> 00:01:55.620
And I want to start just by showing you a few beautiful tables I got from the internet.

00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:59.980
So the cool thing about this table here is that it's pretty visually stunning.

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:02.940
It has all the parts that I like in a table.

00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:03.940
Like look at this header.

00:02:03.940 --> 00:02:08.300
Basically it just has a title and a subtitle, but what it does is it explains the purpose

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:09.300
of the table.

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:13.660
Before you see anything else, you sort of see what the table really is supposed to drive

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:14.660
at.

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:16.059
Another cool thing I like is that there's a spanner.

00:02:16.059 --> 00:02:19.699
What that means is there's a label above a number of columns.

00:02:19.699 --> 00:02:24.139
It just gives you some sort of grouping and some structure to the table.

00:02:24.139 --> 00:02:26.220
And another cool thing is these team logos.

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:29.339
They quickly convey the identity of each row.

00:02:29.339 --> 00:02:30.580
And formatting.

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:32.059
That's a thing here.

00:02:32.059 --> 00:02:36.860
We see that we have percentage values, and they're nicely formatted for readability.

00:02:36.860 --> 00:02:40.300
And the really cool thing is that this row here, the second row, is highlighted, and

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:43.940
it essentially draws attention to the main subject of the table.

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:48.259
I won't get into that right, what it is, but it's a key part of the data visualization.

00:02:48.259 --> 00:02:54.619
It gives you the focus and it drives you to the insight pretty fast.

00:02:54.619 --> 00:02:59.059
And so I have another table from the same author, coincidentally.

00:02:59.059 --> 00:03:02.899
What really grabbed me about this table is that there's bar charts inside this table.

00:03:02.899 --> 00:03:07.300
You can see right here, quite a few of them, they're front and center.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.899
And what they do is they enable really fast comparisons between values here.

00:03:10.899 --> 00:03:14.820
If you just have the numbers, like the percentage values, it wouldn't be so highly readable,

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:15.940
but we have both.

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:18.979
We have the bars plus the precise values.

00:03:18.979 --> 00:03:23.660
Another cool thing is that we have lots of rows, but what the author did was subdivide

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:27.660
the rows into categories or little groups for a better organization.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:28.660
So that's great.

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:35.500
If you want to focus on, like, the box scores or the shooting part or some advanced stats,

00:03:35.500 --> 00:03:40.139
you can focus on them one bit at a time without the entire table overwhelming you.

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:44.500
Another cool thing is that we have a footer here, and in that footer, the author chose

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:47.899
to put in some footnotes, and that provides additional detail.

00:03:47.899 --> 00:03:50.059
It didn't have to be put in the text.

00:03:50.059 --> 00:03:51.339
It could just be put right in the table.

00:03:51.339 --> 00:03:53.539
So that's a really cool thing that the author did.

00:03:53.539 --> 00:03:57.380
Okay, here's a third beautiful table I grabbed from the internet.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:03:58.699
This is sort of a big one.

00:03:58.699 --> 00:04:02.300
It's a lot of numbers, but the cool thing about it is that there's essentially a heat

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:03.979
map in this table.

00:04:03.979 --> 00:04:08.220
We see lots of color, and the color is actually pretty good because it tells you what the

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:12.699
values are without you having to look and parse each and every single value.

00:04:12.699 --> 00:04:16.940
You sort of get an idea just from, like, the colors presented.

00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:19.540
And there's a number of good things I like about this table.

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:24.859
Besides the heat map, we have nicely formatted percentage values, and we noticed that if

00:04:24.859 --> 00:04:30.619
you look really closely, the percentage values have decimal alignment, which makes for easy

00:04:30.619 --> 00:04:33.980
readability of the values, which is really a nice touch.

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:38.059
And of course, the heat map, like I said before, it helps you scan the values, and it really

00:04:38.059 --> 00:04:42.019
aids comparisons without having to read every single value.

00:04:42.019 --> 00:04:44.859
So the really cool thing about these tables is they're not made in Illustrator, they're

00:04:44.859 --> 00:04:49.500
not made in some graphics program, they're made from code.

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:54.739
And of course, the benefit from that is that we get a reproducible workflow.

00:04:54.739 --> 00:05:00.059
You go from input data to analysis to visualization, which is this, and you can bring that right

00:05:00.059 --> 00:05:01.059
to reporting.

00:05:01.059 --> 00:05:05.700
And you don't have to, you know, go to another program, dump the value, dump the data out,

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:08.380
and then, like, you know, use some other tool.

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:12.859
You have one continuous reproducible workflow, which is very cool.

00:05:12.859 --> 00:05:15.739
So how did we get here to this point where we can make tables from code?

00:05:15.739 --> 00:05:21.700
Well, we had to generate an API, but before we create that API, we had to look, you know,

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:26.339
at, you know, the state of the art in terms of, like, what's done for tables.

00:05:26.339 --> 00:05:31.019
Surprisingly, and this is something that made me a little bit upset, is that there weren't

00:05:31.019 --> 00:05:35.140
many texts at all for table design.

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:36.380
So we had to look really, really hard.

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:37.380
You know, lots of books here.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:39.540
These are great for everything else.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:42.660
But luckily, we found one book, which was great.

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:45.179
It's a pretty old one, but it's a great one.

00:05:45.179 --> 00:05:48.059
It's the Census Manual of Tabular Presentation.

00:05:48.059 --> 00:05:49.059
What does it do?

00:05:49.059 --> 00:05:52.579
Well, it essentially dials the concepts on table display to 11.

00:05:52.579 --> 00:05:55.859
It provides many solid and useful recommendations.

00:05:55.859 --> 00:06:01.619
It has nearly 300 pages of, you know, just table stuff, which is really great.

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:05.100
The most important thing is right away it formalizes the structure of a table.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:06.100
We don't have to go too far.

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:09.220
It's actually in figure two of this whole book.

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:13.700
It gets right down to just showing you what the different parts of a table are called

00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:16.299
and how they're structured and what they do.

00:06:16.299 --> 00:06:22.779
So we took that because these are really great ideas, and we adapted it to a sort of a more

00:06:22.779 --> 00:06:25.380
modern, you know, version of a table.

00:06:25.380 --> 00:06:26.380
And we got this.

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:31.980
So we have the different parts, like the table header, the stub, and table footer, and all

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:32.980
the other parts.

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:35.899
And we gave them names, which was super important.

00:06:35.899 --> 00:06:37.980
So how do you make tables today?

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:40.980
Sort of like looking at how people do it.

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:42.660
You may take a raw data frame.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:45.660
This is, I believe, a polders data frame.

00:06:45.660 --> 00:06:50.179
You can present it to other people like this, just like, here you go, the raw data frame.

00:06:50.179 --> 00:06:52.140
This is your results.

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:56.739
Not really recommended because it doesn't look too good and also doesn't have all the

00:06:56.739 --> 00:06:57.739
data.

00:06:57.739 --> 00:06:58.739
It's kind of like not so great.

00:06:58.739 --> 00:06:59.739
It's a bit raw.

00:06:59.739 --> 00:07:00.739
Another idea.

00:07:00.739 --> 00:07:01.739
This is what a lot of people do.

00:07:01.739 --> 00:07:02.940
I'm guilty of this.

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:05.980
You can bring your data to Excel and then make the table there.

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:11.500
Now, the problem is, and this is what I discussed before, is that now your workflow is not reproducible.

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:13.940
It's a bit broken in that way.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:14.940
So not great.

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:19.100
I mean, you got the table done, but, you know, at the expense of like breaking your reproducible

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:20.779
workflow.

00:07:20.779 --> 00:07:25.540
So our idea is you can use an API like great tables and work entirely in Python.

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:27.540
It's reproducible.

00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:29.500
Probably less effort overall.

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:30.899
And the tables look really good.

00:07:30.899 --> 00:07:34.859
So you're not losing anything by keeping it in Python.

00:07:34.859 --> 00:07:37.820
You're actually getting a lot because it's pretty great.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:38.820
Okay.

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:39.820
So great tables.

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:40.820
It's our package.

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:42.339
It's focused purely on the display of tables.

00:07:42.339 --> 00:07:44.579
That's its only concern.

00:07:44.579 --> 00:07:46.859
It's definitely not the only approach in Python.

00:07:46.859 --> 00:07:50.579
But we do promise you that it's comprehensive, actively developed.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:53.859
And it tries to go deep on all table related problems.

00:07:53.859 --> 00:07:57.619
So throughout the rest of this talk, we'll use great tables and illustrate the process

00:07:57.619 --> 00:08:01.480
and design behind making presentation quality tables.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:06.579
And for that, I'm going to give you Michael again, and he'll focus on the key ingredients

00:08:06.579 --> 00:08:08.579
of making a great table.

00:08:08.579 --> 00:08:09.579
Oh, yeah.

00:08:09.579 --> 00:08:10.579
Nice.

00:08:10.579 --> 00:08:11.579
Thanks.

00:08:11.579 --> 00:08:16.579
So I'm going to walk through how to go from a sort of plain data frame to a beautiful

00:08:16.579 --> 00:08:18.339
display table.

00:08:18.339 --> 00:08:23.779
And the three key ingredients I'll talk about are structure, format, and style.

00:08:23.779 --> 00:08:29.779
So basically, structure is adding parts to the table that are sort of outside the data

00:08:29.779 --> 00:08:30.779
itself.

00:08:30.779 --> 00:08:33.859
So notice that here we've added a title.

00:08:33.859 --> 00:08:38.419
And we have some column spanners, which actually go over the column labels and give us some

00:08:38.419 --> 00:08:41.739
good grouping information around columns.

00:08:41.739 --> 00:08:46.900
And then we formatted the column labels themselves so that they're a little bit cleaner.

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:48.739
There are no underscores.

00:08:48.739 --> 00:08:52.260
Things are in title case and a little bit easier to read.

00:08:52.260 --> 00:08:54.619
The next piece is formatting.

00:08:54.619 --> 00:08:59.940
So formatting, for example, is changing the actual data values.

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:03.460
So notice that we have compact dollar values.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:08.380
So we're using things like K to mean thousands and M to mean millions.

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:12.739
This is common in some domains like some government domains on tables.

00:09:12.739 --> 00:09:16.820
They like to report out using these compact formats.

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:20.140
We've also formatted the percentages just to clean them up.

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:23.500
So they're whole numbers, and they have a percentage sign after them.

00:09:23.500 --> 00:09:26.299
And the last piece is styling.

00:09:26.299 --> 00:09:31.140
So for style, we're going to fill the background of some columns to group them together.

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:35.880
So notice the revenue columns are blue, but they have a blue background.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.099
And the profit columns have a papaya whip background.

00:09:39.099 --> 00:09:43.900
The bottom row is the text is bolded to emphasize that it's a total.

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:47.700
I just want to emphasize that one of these columns, a percentage column,

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:52.219
sums up to 102%, which is not a great tables problem.

00:09:52.219 --> 00:09:54.099
It's a Michael Chao problem.

00:09:54.099 --> 00:09:57.260
I screwed the data up before this talk.

00:09:57.260 --> 00:10:00.140
But hopefully, it's not too distracting.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:04.700
I just wanted to own that before you owned me and dragged me

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:08.299
through the internet for my terrible addition skills.

00:10:08.299 --> 00:10:11.380
All right, so we're going to go through these step by step

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:15.099
to show what they might look like in code.

00:10:15.099 --> 00:10:21.179
The very first thing we need to do is some imports and a little bit of Polars explanation.

00:10:21.179 --> 00:10:26.539
So first, we import from GreatTables the GT object.

00:10:26.539 --> 00:10:33.020
That's the thing we use all throughout GreatTables to format the tables.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.460
So for Polars, we're going to use Polars DataFrames.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:38.900
So Polars is a library for data analysis.

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:43.020
And the one thing we need to mention is these polar selectors.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:46.340
So we're going to import polar selectors as CS.

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:51.340
And the one thing that this lets us do is it lets us select groups of columns really easily.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:58.179
So we can say things like CS.startsWithRevenue to choose all the columns that begin with revenue.

00:10:58.179 --> 00:11:00.940
So it's a really convenient tool that we'll use throughout.

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:07.140
But we just wanted to flag it up front so you can get a sense for what's going on in the examples.

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:08.500
All right.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:13.219
So looking at the first piece structure, this is the plain table output.

00:11:13.219 --> 00:11:16.419
And we're going to add some parts to it.

00:11:16.419 --> 00:11:20.619
So the first part is tab header.

00:11:20.619 --> 00:11:24.619
Tab header just adds a simple title to the table.

00:11:24.619 --> 00:11:28.299
This is a really small piece, but it's probably the most important part of the table.

00:11:28.299 --> 00:11:33.619
Because in the information hierarchy, the title says what people are even looking at.

00:11:33.619 --> 00:11:40.340
It's probably the most important piece of information if someone has three seconds to figure out what's going on.

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:44.099
So the next piece we'll add is a tab spanner.

00:11:44.099 --> 00:11:48.179
And this is just a label over the columns to group them together.

00:11:48.179 --> 00:11:49.659
So here we have revenue.

00:11:49.659 --> 00:11:57.500
And notice that we're just putting this label over the revenue columns so that people can see they're grouped a bit more easily.

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:05.179
And we'll go ahead and do it to the profit columns just to have a similar spanner.

00:12:05.179 --> 00:12:09.340
And then to finish off, we're going to rename the columns.

00:12:09.340 --> 00:12:16.299
So notice before we were repeating in the column name words like revenue that we now have in the spanners.

00:12:16.299 --> 00:12:20.260
So we're going to go through and clean them up so that extra information is gone.

00:12:20.260 --> 00:12:25.059
And people can just see revenue in the spanner and amount in the column label.

00:12:25.059 --> 00:12:27.419
So now things are quick to read.

00:12:27.419 --> 00:12:30.179
So the next piece is formatting.

00:12:30.179 --> 00:12:34.380
And here we use these methods that start with .fmt.

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:36.659
So the first piece is format percent.

00:12:36.659 --> 00:12:42.059
And here we're using a polar selector to get all the columns ending with percent, PCT.

00:12:42.059 --> 00:12:44.979
And we're cutting out their decimals.

00:12:44.979 --> 00:12:50.179
And so notice the columns flagged in purple now are formatted as percentages.

00:12:50.179 --> 00:12:51.780
And they don't have any trailing decimals.

00:12:51.780 --> 00:12:53.900
They're just whole numbers.

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:56.059
The second piece is format number.

00:12:56.059 --> 00:12:58.539
This is the piece we use to make the number compact.

00:12:58.539 --> 00:13:06.979
So instead of being written out with all of its zeros, now it's shortened to have K for thousands and M for millions.

00:13:06.979 --> 00:13:10.619
And so that's it for formatting.

00:13:10.619 --> 00:13:12.539
The last piece is styling.

00:13:12.539 --> 00:13:17.140
So for styling, we'll use the .tabstyle method.

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:21.500
And the key to this is .tabstyle takes two arguments.

00:13:21.500 --> 00:13:23.059
So one is location.

00:13:23.059 --> 00:13:27.739
Basically, that's where in the table you want to apply the style.

00:13:27.739 --> 00:13:29.460
And the second is style.

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:32.940
And that's the actual styling you want to do.

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:37.299
So it's sort of the where versus the what that you want to do for style.

00:13:37.299 --> 00:13:40.859
So in this example, we're styling the body.

00:13:40.859 --> 00:13:46.260
So look.body means the actual data in the table.

00:13:46.260 --> 00:13:50.380
And we're selecting specific columns, the revenue columns.

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:54.179
And style.fill means we want to fill the background.

00:13:54.179 --> 00:13:57.859
And in this case, we're filling it Alice blue.

00:13:57.859 --> 00:14:04.140
So this is just to make the revenue columns group together visually.

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:09.419
So in green, the code flagged in green is we apply it again to profit.

00:14:09.419 --> 00:14:15.859
And we do something similar, but this time we make the profit columns have a papaya whip background.

00:14:15.859 --> 00:14:19.179
And then the last thing is a little bit different.

00:14:19.179 --> 00:14:24.539
Instead of formatting columns, so before we made the backgrounds of the columns a color,

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:26.099
we target a row.

00:14:26.099 --> 00:14:30.260
So if you look at the very bottom of the table, the text is bolded.

00:14:30.260 --> 00:14:33.619
What we do here is we use the location.

00:14:33.619 --> 00:14:35.780
We can use pollers expressions.

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:40.340
So these are little pieces of data analysis, essentially.

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:48.299
So here, the rows equals part is using a pollers expression to basically filter out

00:14:48.299 --> 00:14:52.140
the bottom row of the table for styling.

00:14:52.140 --> 00:14:57.580
And then the style piece, we use style.text to make it bold.

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:02.859
So the key is there's a whole range of styles that we can apply to a variety of places.

00:15:02.859 --> 00:15:04.260
All right.

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:08.020
So that was the basics of structure, formatting, and style.

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:11.739
One other exciting piece is we can add images and plots.

00:15:11.739 --> 00:15:16.940
So on the left, we've added some images with format image.

00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:21.059
This is really nice because people can now see really quickly different products.

00:15:21.059 --> 00:15:25.260
So if they're looking for a specific thing like filters, they can hopefully pick it out

00:15:25.260 --> 00:15:26.619
really fast visually.

00:15:26.619 --> 00:15:31.380
Nanoplots on the right, so those are those tiny bar charts, are neat.

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:34.059
They can display little trends in the table.

00:15:34.059 --> 00:15:38.539
And these are really powerful because they combine some of the quick insight and

00:15:38.539 --> 00:15:44.979
trend spotting of a traditional plot with the compactness of a table.

00:15:44.979 --> 00:15:49.059
So those are two bonus ingredients that great tables can put in.

00:15:49.059 --> 00:15:54.820
So that was the key ingredients for going from a plain unstyled data frame through

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:59.099
great tables to a table that's ready for display.

00:15:59.099 --> 00:16:04.179
So next, Rich will talk a bit about some advanced designs like nanoplots,

00:16:04.179 --> 00:16:06.700
culling, and formatting.

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:08.619
Sweet. Thanks, Michael.

00:16:08.619 --> 00:16:12.700
So I want to talk to you about one method we have in our package, and it's really

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:15.460
quite nice, format nanoplot.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:19.859
I like to call them small plots within table cells that give you really compact

00:16:19.859 --> 00:16:22.580
visualizations that can reveal trends in the data.

00:16:22.580 --> 00:16:24.940
And they're quite fun to use as well.

00:16:24.940 --> 00:16:30.580
Like, for instance, you might notice right away that the cold brew row is,

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:31.940
well, it's a little bit strange.

00:16:31.940 --> 00:16:33.659
I mean, you can just sort of see the pattern right there.

00:16:33.659 --> 00:16:39.419
It increases in summer to a maximum, and other parts of the year aren't so great.

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:40.780
And also, espresso machines.

00:16:40.780 --> 00:16:46.219
Seems like we have intermittent sales, and, you know, like some months are fantastic.

00:16:46.219 --> 00:16:48.619
Other months have zero sales.

00:16:48.619 --> 00:16:49.979
And you can get that right away with nanoplots.

00:16:49.979 --> 00:16:55.099
These bar plots, this bar plot version of nanoplots, you can see those patterns right away.

00:16:55.099 --> 00:16:56.380
So really kind of cool.

00:16:56.380 --> 00:16:59.659
Better than just numbers by themselves, for sure.

00:16:59.659 --> 00:17:04.979
So why did we make this sort of method to generate nanoplots?

00:17:04.979 --> 00:17:08.300
Well, they were inspired by sparklines, and you may have heard of those.

00:17:08.300 --> 00:17:10.540
They were popularized by Tufti.

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:15.219
And if you didn't hear of it that way, you probably heard of it through Microsoft Excel,

00:17:15.219 --> 00:17:18.819
because there's an implementation of that in Excel.

00:17:18.819 --> 00:17:19.819
And people really like that feature.

00:17:19.819 --> 00:17:22.819
I see that stuff all over the place when people are talking about Excel.

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:29.020
So sparklines are really cool, and they work in tables, as we can see that it works in Excel.

00:17:29.020 --> 00:17:32.099
So we have a different version of a nanoplot here.

00:17:32.099 --> 00:17:35.260
Basically, these are like line-based nanoplots.

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:39.500
And it's really kind of cool, because in a table like this, you want your time to insight

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:41.020
to be really minimized.

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:47.339
This is essentially a table of daily tests performed on a patient, measurements from

00:17:47.339 --> 00:17:50.739
day three to day eight.

00:17:50.739 --> 00:17:55.780
And we can sort of see the progression of these different lab tests day after day.

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:58.099
Some of these trends go up, some go down.

00:17:58.099 --> 00:17:59.099
Maybe they're not so good.

00:17:59.099 --> 00:18:01.099
Maybe they're just fine.

00:18:01.099 --> 00:18:03.900
We can see right here, WBC, white blood cell count.

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:08.020
It's increasing beyond the normal range, a little bit scary.

00:18:08.020 --> 00:18:12.140
But no matter, we can sort of see that right away with this nanoplot.

00:18:12.140 --> 00:18:15.260
And nanoplots are really cool, because they're interactive.

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:20.339
You can just hover over different values, like different points, and get a readout,

00:18:20.339 --> 00:18:22.420
which is really kind of neat.

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:25.660
So you can either just look at it or explore a little bit.

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:31.180
So inviting that interactivity is kind of a cool feature we wanted from day one when

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:32.780
designing these nanoplots.

00:18:32.859 --> 00:18:35.339
Okay, and they're really flexible, too.

00:18:35.339 --> 00:18:37.859
They can be styled in many different ways.

00:18:37.859 --> 00:18:40.660
And because of that, they can be used in many different contexts.

00:18:40.660 --> 00:18:44.859
Like for instance, stock prices, there's a table right there showing them.

00:18:44.859 --> 00:18:46.660
Nanoplots are pretty good for that sort of thing.

00:18:46.660 --> 00:18:51.699
Weather data, there's temperatures, also pretty good, because you can sort of compare lots

00:18:51.699 --> 00:18:55.619
of different places and get your weather data that way.

00:18:55.619 --> 00:18:58.739
You can also make it such that you have a little scatterplot.

00:18:58.739 --> 00:19:03.619
So sales data is like throughout a day, that's not a bad thing to plot, and you can hover

00:19:03.619 --> 00:19:09.140
over those values and sort of see how the sales went throughout the day.

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:11.780
Another thing we have is data color.

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:14.540
It allows you to create heatmaps and tables.

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:16.979
So here's that table we showed earlier.

00:19:16.979 --> 00:19:19.739
It's actually generated through gray tables.

00:19:19.739 --> 00:19:25.500
And with data color, it allows you to generate a heatmap with a palette of your choosing.

00:19:25.500 --> 00:19:29.660
So essentially, it makes the large amount of data presented in this table much easier

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:31.339
to digest at a glance.

00:19:31.339 --> 00:19:33.939
You don't have to look just at a wall of numbers.

00:19:33.939 --> 00:19:38.540
You've actually got these colored cells to help you out.

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:41.780
And because of that, you can see large values right away.

00:19:41.780 --> 00:19:46.780
Any sort of negligible or small values, they sort of lack that color, because what's been

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:50.859
done is that the low ends are sort of faded out.

00:19:50.859 --> 00:19:54.699
So that's quite nice to see and really easy to parse.

00:19:54.699 --> 00:20:01.699
So big two advantages we take from plots in tables with this are emphasizing differences

00:20:01.699 --> 00:20:05.140
in values and revealing trends in the data.

00:20:05.140 --> 00:20:06.660
So let me just show you.

00:20:06.660 --> 00:20:11.020
In a row, for instance, you can compare across measures, right?

00:20:11.020 --> 00:20:13.060
So you're just looking at the France row.

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:19.300
You can see what energy mix there is just right away just by scanning back and forth.

00:20:19.300 --> 00:20:23.699
Looking up and down a column, you can compare values across observations.

00:20:23.699 --> 00:20:27.939
So we can see here, CO2 intensity, it increases as you go down the table.

00:20:27.939 --> 00:20:33.660
And so we sort of see the ranking, the relative ranking of these different observations.

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:37.219
And globally, we can see a pattern across the table, which is really nice.

00:20:37.219 --> 00:20:41.020
So the trend we see here is sort of like moving from the top left to the bottom right.

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:43.780
Basically, it boils down to energy from fossil fuels.

00:20:43.780 --> 00:20:45.660
It leads to higher CO2 intensity values.

00:20:45.660 --> 00:20:46.819
That's how the table's organized.

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:51.260
But you can sort of see the extent to how this plays out in the table.

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:55.579
Okay, another big thing we have inside grade tables is formatting methods.

00:20:55.579 --> 00:20:58.780
And we saw some of that earlier in Michael's demonstration.

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:01.739
They are really powerful, and there's quite a few of them.

00:21:01.739 --> 00:21:04.060
So what we can do with them is format numbers, dates,

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:08.099
and strings with flexible and powerful methods.

00:21:08.099 --> 00:21:11.180
So, for instance, we take this unformatted column of values.

00:21:11.180 --> 00:21:12.540
We can just write number.

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:16.939
And right away, we can get a thing like a fixed number of decimal places

00:21:16.939 --> 00:21:20.260
and also these grouping separators in the large part of the number.

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:22.459
So it makes it easier to read these numbers.

00:21:22.459 --> 00:21:26.500
If you don't really care about the decimal part, we can use format integer,

00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:29.660
and it'll do the rounding for you and still have grouping separators.

00:21:29.660 --> 00:21:32.140
So these are great for counts, for instance.

00:21:32.140 --> 00:21:36.339
Sometimes your values are either extremely large or very small.

00:21:36.339 --> 00:21:38.380
And for that, and especially in certain domains,

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:43.500
you might want to use format scientific to get your values in scientific notation.

00:21:43.500 --> 00:21:46.859
And it's quite easy to do that with that method.

00:21:46.859 --> 00:21:50.060
Another thing is formatting as percentage values.

00:21:50.060 --> 00:21:52.339
We can do that with format percent.

00:21:52.339 --> 00:21:55.579
And if you have currency values, we can use format currency.

00:21:55.579 --> 00:22:00.219
And the great thing about that is you can provide any currency code that you want,

00:22:00.219 --> 00:22:03.300
and great tables will understand how to format that

00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:08.579
in terms of the number of decimal places and the currency sign to use.

00:22:08.579 --> 00:22:10.939
We run pretty deep when it comes to formatting methods.

00:22:10.939 --> 00:22:17.099
So we have all sorts of them, and that includes formatting as bytes as well.

00:22:17.099 --> 00:22:23.459
So you provide a number, and format bytes will give you the byte size of that number.

00:22:23.459 --> 00:22:27.140
And with all these formatting methods, we have certain common arguments,

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:28.739
and one of them is pattern.

00:22:28.739 --> 00:22:30.819
It just allows you to decorate your formatted value

00:22:30.819 --> 00:22:34.219
with any sort of string literals you want around that.

00:22:34.219 --> 00:22:36.859
Yeah, and as I said before, there's many more available.

00:22:36.859 --> 00:22:42.380
You can format dates, times, you can add images, you could format text as markdown.

00:22:42.380 --> 00:22:43.579
And there's many more in development

00:22:43.579 --> 00:22:47.060
because it's a pretty sort of fundamental part of this package.

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:50.819
So to sum up, Michael, would you take this away?

00:22:50.819 --> 00:22:54.699
I hope we make the case that making beautiful publication-quality tables in Python

00:22:54.699 --> 00:22:58.300
is not only possible in 2024, but it's actually really great.

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:01.099
We think tables are really cool, and we think,

00:23:01.099 --> 00:23:03.979
well, we're pretty sure people love good-looking tables.

00:23:03.979 --> 00:23:08.180
Sending a polished table is a chance to make a really great first impression,

00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:11.060
and it tells people it's worth paying attention to.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:15.739
And there's so much at your disposal to help group information and highlight things

00:23:15.739 --> 00:23:18.300
that there's a lot of really great stuff in great tables

00:23:18.300 --> 00:23:20.979
for really bringing out the best in your data.

00:23:20.979 --> 00:23:24.140
We talked a bit about the reproducibility chain

00:23:24.140 --> 00:23:27.020
that you probably already spend a lot of work.

00:23:27.020 --> 00:23:31.099
You worked really hard to be sure that your data and your analysis

00:23:31.099 --> 00:23:34.540
and a lot of your visualizations are already in Python.

00:23:34.540 --> 00:23:39.099
The neat thing about great tables is now you don't have to pluck your data into Excel.

00:23:39.099 --> 00:23:42.380
You can keep going with your Python scripts

00:23:42.380 --> 00:23:48.900
and have one single sort of tool chain to go from input data to reporting.

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:52.660
The best way to get started is to pip install great tables.

00:23:52.660 --> 00:23:56.780
We have a website, which is positdev.github.io

00:23:56.780 --> 00:23:58.900
slash great hyphen tables.

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:02.060
We've tried to really fill it with a lot of examples.

00:24:02.060 --> 00:24:04.579
And along the way, as we've developed great tables,

00:24:04.579 --> 00:24:09.780
we've tried to blog and document what we think are some core problems

00:24:09.780 --> 00:24:12.979
that we've been chipping away at and trying to solve.

00:24:12.979 --> 00:24:16.219
So hopefully there are a lot of really nice nuggets there

00:24:16.219 --> 00:24:20.180
about table display and things we've learned along the way.

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:22.540
Thank you so much for watching this.

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:27.180
And we hope that you have a lot of beautiful table use cases

00:24:27.180 --> 00:24:30.380
that you'll be able to throw great tables at.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:31.420
See y'all.

00:24:31.420 --> 00:24:33.780
Hope you make a lot of beautiful tables.

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:34.979
Keep making those tables.

00:24:34.979 --> 00:24:38.420
♪♪♪

